<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="dna-structure">DNA: Structure</h2><ul><li><p>The nucleic acid DNA is a <b>polynucleotide</b> – it is made up of <b>many nucleotides</b> bonded together in a <b>long chain</b></p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="DNA nucleotide with carbon numbers" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="606" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/DNA-nucleotide-with-carbon-numbers.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>DNA nucleotide</b></i></p><ul><li><p>DNA molecules are made up of <b>two polynucleotide strands</b> lying side by side, running in opposite directions – the strands are said to be <b>antiparallel</b></p></li><li><p>Each DNA polynucleotide strand is made up of <b>alternating deoxyribose sugars and phosphate groups bonded together </b>to form the <b>sugar-phosphate backbone.</b> These bonds are <b>covalent</b> <b>bonds</b> known as <b>phosphodiester bonds</b></p><ul><li><p>The phosphodiester bonds link the <b>5-carbon of one deoxyribose sugar</b> molecule to the phosphate group from the same nucleotide, which is itself linked by another phosphodiester bond to the <b>3-carbon of the deoxyribose sugar molecule of the next nucleotide </b>in the strand</p></li><li><p>Each DNA polynucleotide strand is said to have a <b>3’ end and a 5’ end</b> (these numbers relate to which carbon on the pentose sugar could be bonded with another nucleotide)</p></li><li><p>As the strands run in opposite directions (they are <b>antiparallel</b>), one is known as the <b>5’ to 3’ strand</b> and the other is known as the <b>3’ to 5’ strand</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>The nitrogenous bases of each nucleotide project out from the backbone towards the interior of the double-stranded DNA molecule</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="A single DNA polynucleotide strand" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1031" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/A-single-DNA-polynucleotide-strand.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>A single DNA polynucleotide strand</b></i></p><h4 id="hydrogen-bonding">Hydrogen bonding</h4><ul><li><p>The two antiparallel DNA polynucleotide strands that make up the DNA molecule are <b>held together by hydrogen bonds</b> between the nitrogenous bases</p></li><li><p>These hydrogen bonds always occur between the <b>same pairs of bases</b>:</p><ul><li><p>The purine <b>adenine</b> (A) always pairs with the pyrimidine <b>thymine</b> (T) – two hydrogen bonds are formed between these bases</p></li><li><p>The purine <b>guanine</b> (G) always pairs with the pyrimidine <b>cytosine</b> (C) – three hydrogen bonds are formed between these bases</p></li><li><p>This is known as <b>complementary base pairing</b></p></li><li><p>These pairs are known as <b>DNA base pairs</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="DNA molecule with hydrogen bonding" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="833" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/02/DNA-molecule-with-hydrogen-bonding.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>A section of DNA showing hydrogen bonding between base pairs</b></i></p><h4 id="double-helix">Double helix</h4><ul><li><p>DNA is not two-dimensional as seen in the diagram above</p></li><li><p>DNA is described as a <span class="popovers" data-content="A helix is a shape like a corkscrew or a spiral staircase. DNA is described as a double helix as it is made up of two strands that spiral around each other in this way." data-title="Double Helix" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">double helix</span></p></li><li><p>This refers to the <b>three-dimensional shape</b> that DNA molecules form</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="DNA double helix formation" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1186" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/27.-DNA-double-helix-formation.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>DNA molecules form a 3D double helix structure</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>Make sure you can name the different components of a DNA molecule (sugar-phosphate backbone, nucleotide, complementary base pairs, phosphodiester bonds, hydrogen bonds) and make sure you are able to locate these on a diagram.</p><p>Remember that <b>phosphodiester bonds</b> join the nucleotides in the sugar-phosphate backbone, and <b>hydrogen bonds</b> join the bases of the two complementary strands together.</p><p>Remember that the bases are complementary, so the number of A = T and C = G. You could be asked to determine how many bases are present in a DNA molecule if given the number of just one of the bases.</p></div></div></div></div>